static memes and an additional origin which explains humanity's long period of stagnation.
Memes:
generated in the mind
mutate in the mind
influenced by our biological brain
and young children

we can generate them by using creativity
to replicate meaning. This is the same mechanism
needed to create them.

so they can be generated without interpreting another's
behaviour provided theres some comparably good
explanation for why they'd be generated

the exact memes are generated depend on
the person's mental state; their environment,
e.g. natural selection pressures, or their tribe and
relevant memes; and the other ideas and memes
they have already.

a consistent set up works for consistent replication
(e.g. being treated badly during school w/ reward based
on conformity).

so if we had a consistent set up and a reason for creative
effort to be spent, it only needs to be consistent
for every culture over 180k years

creativity was used in static societies
to do replication well and thus impress
people and the tribe.

`Status in such a society is reduced by
transgressing peoples expectations of
proper behaviour, and is improved by
meeting them.` DD, BoI, Ch16

There was a selection pressure in favour of
those ppl better capable of satisfying
other ppl and the rest of the tribe's expectations.

relevant selection pressures are:
1. Existing memes to suppress competitors
(including newer versions of itself)
2. continue satisfying behavioural requirements
well, even if it means the person knowlingly
pretends to believe a lie, thats okay as long as the
behaviour, and thus replication, persist.

Parents want children who also satisfy tribal
expectations and their own (even if they know
their own are arbitrary)
(p23c)
applys to memes; existential risk
applys to genes

it could be replaced by a better version,
or be kicked out entirely

occasionally, someone will seem to loose faith
or change their mind on something out of nowhere.
The trigger can be otherwise
small and insignificant. Some of the time,
Is this why?

Futher selection pressure in favour of
static memes. i.e. to direct creativity away
from rationality. Any other subject is better. other
memes are a less risky target than itself, and
and applying creativity to them might reduce competition
as a bonus.

Memes experience selection pressure which directs
creativity to **mutate other memes** _and_ itself,
provided the resulting behavioural expressions
of the mutation matchs expectations.

memes are most powerful when they can be expressed, and
anti-rational people are more suceptabile the more
creative they are _at meeting expectations_.
Botin increase with age (at least for a while)

**more creativity means memes are more significant.**
survival is less luck based because we're smarter,
which *increases* importance of a good, safe early
childhood (after which the brain does more work)
(p29c)

How do parents and tribe come to be satisfied?
(p29d)

We evolved from advanced apes with
some capacity for memetic information.
(BoI)

The biological brain alters which
memes can and can't be replicated
through us depending on creativity
and storeage capacity.

`our inborn capacity for reasoning itself
is software` and we could have other
inborn ideas too. curi.us/1531/#11672

when people are young, these inborn ideas are
our starting point, and we have to interpret
everything through and with them till we learn better.

these ideas have made the jump to universality.
they have reach. losing them is too expensive,
but they're hard to change. so selection pressure
ends up being applied elsewhere:
other companion inborn ideas.

they were crucial for competetiveness so were
selected for.

inborn capacity for reasoning is difficult to remove,
so can be a consistent factor for 180k years.

they were hard to vary, and thus resilient to
genetic mutation.

children are very creative, but also not bound
by taboo and the existing meme-pool.

are mistreated to some degree from birth
(or close enough to not matter)

degree doesn't matter that much. no child developes
faster because they're *not* being eaten by a lion
a good way to stay alive is meet expectations

but a child needs to be doing this VERY early,
even before they've picked up many or any implicit
ideas

Selection pressure to develop inborn ideas that prepare
for children for the next (say) 5 yrs.
e.g. One safe-ish way to avoid being mistreated even
more is to treat every bad experience as though
you're the problem.

implicit ideas are gathered slowly over first few
years of life and used to build up knowledge of the
world from there, especially via memes.
more memes become available very rapidly.

selection pressure is to maintain anti-rational-
compatible early inborn ideas to maximise chance
of living to the point memes take over.
